It seems to me that businesses that are structured to favor profits over people and to exploit workers would also be more likely to fulfill the predictions of conservative analysts who maintain that businesses would cut jobs and make other strategic adjustments that would hurt workers.  Also, steep wage increases would still likely stress small businesses and cause disruptions that would challenge adaptation, particularly in parts of the country where the minimum wage is relatively low at present, and possibly restrict creativity where flexibility is required and preferred among employer and employee relations and associated initiatives to make businesses more viable.

q97: I have 14 years of multi-unit business management experience. Businesses have their budgets and numbers that work outside of Government Policy. A mandatory increase to $15 an hour will do lots of bad changes to the economy. Businesses will reduce the amount of employees they have on staff, increasing unemployment. They will find new ways to do business cheaper than to hire a human, much like app only ordering or closing their Dine-in section. We already see big retailers ending the "cashier" position due to higher wages being required. This also will be fixed with higher prices, so not only will your wage increase, but so will your cost of living. That means it will require more money to pay the current bills you have, meaning you will gain no Value from a wage increase. $15 an hour is not the way to fix the economy. You need competition and the ability for companies to pay employees what they are worth based on skill and business success. A good company will pay employees well regardless of Government policy, so let them grow and employee wages will grow without the need of Washington D.C. to screw it up.
